  <h2>Why I Care About These Two Plastics</h2>

  <p>
    I've been printing parts for boats and cars for a while now. PETG handles a lot. ASA handles more. But there's a ceiling — temperature, chemical exposure, mechanical load — where commodity filaments tap out. That ceiling is where PEEK and PPS live.
  </p>

  <p>
    PEEK (polyether ether ketone) and PPS (polyphenylene sulfide) are engineering thermoplastics that have been standard in aerospace and oil and gas for decades. They survive where everything else fails. The difference now is that printer hardware is finally catching up enough to put these materials in the hands of small shops like mine.
  </p>

  <h2>What Makes Them Different</h2>

  <p>
    Let's keep this simple. PEEK has a continuous service temperature above 250°C. PPS sits around 220°C. Compare that to PETG at 70°C or even ASA at about 95°C. That's not a small gap — it's a different universe.
  </p>

  <p>
    Beyond heat, these materials resist:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Fuel, oil, and hydraulic fluid</strong> — they don't swell, soften, or crack on contact</li>
    <li><strong>Salt water</strong> — critical for anything marine. No degradation over time</li>
    <li><strong>UV exposure</strong> — they hold up in full sun without becoming brittle</li>
    <li><strong>Mechanical fatigue</strong> — parts survive repeated loading cycles that would crack PETG in days</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    PEEK is the stronger of the two but also the more demanding to print. It needs chamber temperatures around 120°C and nozzle temperatures above 400°C. PPS is slightly more forgiving but still requires serious hardware — a standard Bambu or Prusa won't cut it.
  </p>

  <h2>What This Unlocks for Marine Work</h2>

  <p>
    A boat is one of the harshest environments you can put a part into. Salt spray, engine heat, UV, vibration, shock loads. I've had PLA parts turn to mush in a cockpit locker after one summer. PETG lasts longer but still warps near exhaust runs or engine compartments.
  </p>

  <p>
    With PEEK or PPS, I can print parts that sit next to a diesel engine block and survive. Intake manifold adapters. Custom throttle linkage components. Bearing housings that don't need metal. Impeller housings for auxiliary pumps. These are parts that used to require machined Delrin or bronze — now printable on a high-temp machine.
  </p>

  <p>
    For the Newport Bermuda campaign, this is the kind of capability I'm watching closely. Being able to fabricate a replacement part mid-ocean from a material that actually handles the environment — that's not a convenience, it's a safety factor.
  </p>

  <h2>Automotive and Motorsport Applications</h2>

  <p>
    Under a hood, temperatures climb fast. Turbo plumbing, intake runners, sensor mounts near exhaust headers — these are locations where even ABS fails. PPS sensor brackets, PEEK turbo oil drain fittings, heat-resistant wire routing clips. These are real parts on real cars right now, mostly in motorsport, but the technology is trickling down.
  </p>

  <p>
    For classic car restoration — my other obsession — PEEK opens up options for parts that no one manufactures anymore. Carburetor insulators, custom throttle bodies for oddball engines, heat shields. Parts that used to mean a full machine shop job.
  </p>

  <h2>The Catch</h2>

  <p>
    I'm not going to pretend this is cheap. PEEK filament runs $500 to $800 per kilogram. PPS is a bit less but still north of $300/kg. The printers that can handle these materials cost $10,000 and up for anything worth trusting. This isn't hobbyist territory yet.
  </p>

  <p>
    But here's the thing — a single machined PEEK part from a job shop can cost you $200 to $500 for something the size of your thumb. If you're making ten of those a year, the economics shift fast. For a specialty fabrication operation like 3D3D, the investment makes sense because the demand exists.
  </p>

  <h2>Where It's Headed</h2>

  <p>
    The price will come down. It always does. Five years ago, carbon-fibre nylon was exotic. Now I run it every week. PEEK and PPS are on the same trajectory — just further back on the curve. When desktop machines can reliably hit 400°C+ nozzle temps with enclosed chambers, these materials become standard tools.
  </p>

  <p>
    I'm planning our first high-temperature printer acquisition for 2026. When it lands, the range of problems 3D3D can solve expands dramatically. Marine clients, motorsport teams, industrial customers who currently send parts overseas — they'll have a local option that didn't exist before.
  </p>

  <p>
    That's the real story. Not that these materials exist — they've existed for decades. The story is that people like me can finally use them.
  </p>
